              <div class="flex-1">
                <p class="eyebrow text-yellow mb-2">Need this for your farm?</p>
                <p class="font-display text-xl md:text-2xl text-white font-semibold leading-snug">
                  Configure a quote in 90 seconds
                </p>
                <p class="text-white/85 text-sm mt-2 leading-relaxed">
                  Pre-filled for slurry storage — five questions, fixed price back within 24 hours.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-yellow font-bold whitespace-nowrap">
                <span>Start the quote</span>
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 arrow-float" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5">
                  <line x1="5" y1="12" x2="19" y2="12" stroke-linecap="round"/>
                  <polyline points="12 5 19 12 12 19" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
                </svg>
              </div>
            </div>
          </a>
        </aside>

        <!-- Section 4 -->
        <section id="concrete-grade" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">What concrete grade and cement should slurry walls use?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">C40/50 sulphate-resisting concrete is the standard for UK slurry storage.
            That means a characteristic cylinder strength of 40 MPa, cube strength of 50 MPa, and a cement
            blend with low tricalcium aluminate — typically CEM III/B (ground granulated blastfurnace slag) or
            CEM IV (pozzolanic).</strong> It's specified to BS 8500-1 exposure class XA2 or XA3.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Slurry attacks ordinary Portland cement through two mechanisms. Hydrogen sulphide produced by
            anaerobic digestion oxidises to sulphuric acid at the slurry-air interface and dissolves the
            cement paste. Sulphate ions in the slurry react with C3A in the cement to form ettringite,
            which expands and cracks the matrix. Sulphate-resisting blends defeat both.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            We cast every slurry panel in C40/50 SR as standard. Grades below C40/50 are not appropriate for
            slurry duty regardless of how thick the wall is — thickness compensates for structural load,
            not chemistry.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 5 -->
        <section id="reinforcement" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">How much reinforcement and cover do slurry walls need?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">Slurry walls need 50mm minimum cover on the slurry-facing face and 40mm
            on the air face, with reinforcement designed to BS EN 1992-1-1 and BS EN 1992-3.</strong>
            For a 200mm panel that typically means a single mat of B500B mesh at A393 or heavier; for 250mm
            and above, twin mats with bar diameter and spacing tuned to the design moment.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Cover matters more than people think. The Environment Agency's most common reason for failing
            inspection on a slurry tank isn't structural — it's spalling caused by carbonation and chloride
            ingress on under-covered rebar. Once the bar starts to rust, it expands seven-fold and pops the
            cover off. Sufficient cover, properly compacted concrete and a tight crack-width limit (we
            design to 0.2mm) keep the matrix sound.
          </p>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed">
            Joints between panels are sealed with hydrophilic waterstop and a polysulphide or polyurethane
            sealant rated for slurry exposure. The waterstop swells on contact with moisture and
            self-heals minor movement.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 6 -->
        <section id="mistakes" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">What are the most common mistakes on slurry store builds?</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-4">
            <strong class="text-navy">The four mistakes we see most often: under-spec'd concrete (using C32/40 or
            non-sulphate-resisting), inadequate cover at joints, no allowance for vehicle surcharge at the parapet,
            and skipping the 14-day Environment Agency notice.</strong> Any one of those can fail an inspection or
            shorten the life of the asset by a decade.
          </p>
          <ul class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed space-y-3 list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Wrong concrete grade.</strong> C32/40 is fine for a yard slab, not for slurry. Specify C40/50 SR every time.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Joint leakage.</strong> Panels are only as good as the waterstop between them. Skipping or skimping on joint detail is the most common source of leaks.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Surcharge at the parapet.</strong> If a tractor or muck spreader will run within 1.5m of the wall, the design has to account for it. Tell us at design stage, not after pour.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">No EA notice.</strong> WQE1 needs 14 days. Submit it before you break ground or you risk a stop notice.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-navy">Insufficient capacity.</strong> SIG 2026 requires 6 months' storage. Design to capacity, not to budget.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 7 -->
        <section id="checklist" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-4">SSAFO 2018 compliance checklist</h2>
          <p class="text-cast-700 text-lg leading-relaxed mb-6">
            <strong class="text-navy">Run through this list before you sign off design and again before you pour.
            If you can tick all twelve items, your store will pass SSAFO 2018 and qualify for the Slurry
            Infrastructure Grant 2026.</strong>
          </p>
          <div class="bg-bone-200 border-l-4 border-ember p-6 rounded-r">
            <ol class="text-cast-700 text-base leading-relaxed space-y-3 list-decimal pl-5">
              <li>Environment Agency notified (form WQE1) at least 14 days before construction</li>
              <li>Designed to BS 5502-50 and BS EN 1992-3 by a chartered structural engineer</li>
              <li>Minimum 20-year design life specified in writing</li>
              <li>Concrete grade C40/50 with sulphate-resisting cement (CEM III/B or CEM IV)</li>
              <li>Cover to reinforcement: 50mm slurry face, 40mm air face</li>
              <li>Crack width limited to 0.2mm under quasi-permanent loading</li>
              <li>Storage capacity meets or exceeds 6 months of livestock output (AHDB calculator)</li>
              <li>Hydrophilic waterstop and slurry-rated sealant at every joint</li>
              <li>Parapet height minimum 750mm above maximum slurry level</li>
              <li>Vehicle surcharge accounted for if access within 1.5m of wall</li>
              <li>Drainage isolated from clean water (no roof or yard runoff entering store)</li>
              <li>Filling and emptying points designed to prevent overflow</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="mb-12 scroll-mt-24">
          <h2 class="font-display text-3xl text-navy mb-6">Frequently asked questions</h2>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            {faqs.map((f) => (
              <details class="card p-5 group">
